  <div class = 'sectionCon'>
    <div class = 'sectionHead'>Types</div>
    <div class = 'sectionBody'>
      The behaviour of R when it handles data depends on the type of data being processed.
      Data values can be one of six data type, but there are four types that users will
      meet on a regular basis - logical, integer, double and character.
      The type of data can be returned using the <span class = 'inlineF'>typeof</span> function.
    </div>
       
    <div class = 'sectionBody'>
      The simplest of these four main types is logical-type data where values can be one 
      of two values - true or false. The next type is integer-type data, where there 
      is an infinite number of possible
      values but all those values are integers or "whole numbers" - e.g. counts. 
      The third type is double-type, or numeric-type, which is "real numbers" - 
      numbers that can (but don't necessarily) have decimal places - e.g. lengths in 
      centimetres. The final type, the most complex of the four, is character-type data -
      data that can (though, again, does not necessarily) contain non-numeric characters - 
      e.g. names.
    </div>
    
<!--begin.rcode, results = 'hold'
typeof(TRUE)
typeof(1L)
typeof(1.0)
typeof('one')
end.rcode-->

    <div class = 'sectionBody'>
      In the above examples, the logical-type data was the word 'true' written 
      in block capitals - for this data type we can use <span class = 'inline'>TRUE</span> 
      and <span class = 'inline'>TRUE</span> or <span class = 'inline'>T</span> 
      and <span class = 'inline'>F</span>, though the latter two are not 
      best practice because  <span class = 'inline'>T</span> and <span class = 'inline'>F</span>
      can be used as object names so may evaluate to values other than true and false. Integer-type 
      data was specified by giving the integer followed by a capital <span class = 'inline'>L</span>.
      Excluding the <span class = 'inline'>L</span> caused R to evaluate the data as double-type.
      The character-type data was wrapped in quotes - both ' and " can be used. This 
      tells R that the data is character-type. If it were passed as 
      <span class = 'inline'>typeof(one)</span> then R would look for an object in the 
      workspace called one, and return the type of data assigned to that object. 
      Character-type data need not be letters either:
    </div>
  
<!--begin.rcode, results = 'hold'
typeof('1')
end.rcode-->

  </div>




  <div class = 'sectionCon'>
    <a class = "accordion sectionHead">
      <div>Size</div>
      <i class = 'accordionIcon fas fa-plus-circle'></i>
    </a>
    <div class = "panel">
      <div class = "sectionBody">
        The type of data used should always be the most simple that allows the data to retain
        all of its information and necessary functionality. For example, if the data was three
        measurements of 3.2, 4.6, and 5.7, it would make no sense to handle this as logical- 
        or numerical-type - because there is loss of information - and handling this as character-type
        would make it hard to perform processes like calculating averages
      </div>
      
      <div class = "sectionBody">
        Data should also be kept in the simplest form possible while satisfying the above conditions.
        This reduces the size of data in the workspace, improving computational efficiency. This is
        illustrated using the <span class = 'inlineF'>object.size</span> function and the 
        <span class = 'inlineF'>as.*</span> functions.
      </div>

<!--begin.rcode, results = 'hold'
object.size(as.logical(TRUE, FALSE, TRUE))
object.size(as.integer(1L:3L))
object.size(as.numeric(1:3))
object.size(as.character('1', '2', '3'))
end.rcode-->

    </div>
  </div>
</div>

